SIMPLE: weigh
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Weigh
<hw>Weigh</hw> <pr>(w⟦amac⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <fld>(Naut.)</fld>
<def>A corruption of <er>Way</er>, used only in the phrase <cref>under
weigh</cref>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An expedition was got under <qex>weigh</qex> from New York.</q>
<rj><qau>Thackeray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Athenians . . . hurried on board and with considerable
difficulty got under <qex>weigh</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett
(Thucyd.).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weigh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Weigh
<hw>Weigh</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Weighed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Weighing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>weien</ets>,
<ets>weyen</ets>, <ets>weghen</ets>, AS. <ets>wegan</ets> to bear, move;
akin to D. <ets>wegen</ets> to weigh, G. <ets>w⟦aum⟧gen</ets>,
<ets>wiegen</ets>, to weigh, be<ets>wegen</ets> to move, OHG.
<ets>wegan</ets>, Icel. <ets>vega</ets> to move, carry, lift, weigh, Sw.
<ets>v⟦aum⟧ga</ets> to weigh, Dan. <ets>veie</ets>, Goth.
ga<ets>wigan</ets> to shake, L. <ets>vehere</ets> to carry, Skr.
<ets>vah</ets>. <?/<?/<?/<?/. See <er>Way</er>, and cf.
<er>Wey</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To bear up; to raise; to lift into the air; to swing
up; <as>as, to <ex>weigh</ex> anchor</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Weigh</xex>
the vessel up.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To examine by the balance; to ascertain the weight
of, that is, the force with which a thing tends to the center of the
earth; to determine the heaviness, or quantity of matter of; <as>as, to
<ex>weigh</ex> sugar; to <ex>weigh</ex> gold.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou art <qex>weighed</qex> in the balances, and art found
wanting.</q> <rj><qau>Dan. v. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be equivalent to in weight; to counterbalance; to
have the heaviness of.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A body <xex>weighing</xex> divers
ounces.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To pay, allot, take, or give by weight.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>weighed</qex> for my price thirty pieces of silver.</q>
<rj><qau>Zech. xi. 12.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To examine or test as if by the balance; to ponder
in the mind; to consider or examine for the purpose of forming an
opinion or coming to a conclusion; to estimate deliberately and
maturely; to balance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A young man not <qex>weighed</qex> in state affairs.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Had no better <qex>weighed</qex>⟦br⟧
The strength he was to cope with, or his own.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Regard not who it is which speaketh, but <qex>weigh</qex> only
what is spoken.</q> <rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In nice balance, truth with gold she <qex>weighs</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Without sufficiently <qex>weighing</qex> his expressions.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>To consider as worthy of notice; to regard.</def>
<mark>[Obs. or Archaic]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧I <xex>weigh</xex> not you.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All that she so dear did <qex>weigh</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To weigh down</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To
overbalance.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To oppress with weight; to
overburden; to depress.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧To <xex>weigh</xex> thy spirits
<xex>down</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weigh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Weigh
<hw>Weigh</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have
weight; to be heavy.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧They only <xex>weigh</xex> the
heavier.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Cowper.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be considered as important; to have weight in the
intellectual balance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your vows to her and me . . . will even <qex>weigh</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This objection ought to <qex>weigh</qex> with those whose reading
is designed for much talk and little knowledge.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To bear heavily; to press hard.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cleanse the stuffed bosom of that perilous stuff⟦br⟧
Which <qex>weighs</qex> upon the heart.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To judge; to estimate.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Could not <qex>weigh</qex> of worthiness aright.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To weigh down</b></col>, <cd>to sink by its own
weight.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weigh</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Weigh
<hw>Weigh</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Wey</er>.]</ety> <def>A
certain quantity estimated by weight; an English measure of weight. See
<er>Wey</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Weighable</ent>⟦br⟧
